39, 6. excepit: this reading may be defended as in note ad loe, but occepit would be preferable. The codex B (Δ) has only coepit, and the two verbs are frequently confused in MSS. Cp. my note to Diei. 1, 14 (p. 60 edit. maior).

41, 27. vigorem et constantiam et expertum . . . animum] uigorem, constantiam et, etc. - Α (Γ). This reading, though hitherto universally rejected, accords with the consistent practice oi Tacitus in the use of et aiter an asyndeton, the third member being amplified and adding a new aud often, as here, the most important elemeut in the enumeration. cp. Hist. 1.15 (cited iu note oh. 41,17) aud Iatrod. p. xxvru.
